  {
    "@context": "https://schema.org",
    "@type": "FAQPage",
    "mainEntity": [
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How much does it cost to build a 100-room hotel?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "A 100-room limited-service hotel in a mid-tier U.S. market costs roughly $16M–$25M in hard costs. Adding 18–25% for soft costs, land, and pre-opening, total development cost commonly reaches $20M–$32M for a prototypical limited-service project. Full-service or urban projects run materially higher."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "How long does it take to build a hotel from scratch?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "From initial site control to opening day, most hotel projects take 24–48 months. A clean, entitled site with a prototypical brand design can shorten this to 18–24 months. Complex entitlements, custom design, or mixed-use programs routinely push past 36 months."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "Do I need a general contractor who specializes in hotels?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "Yes. Hospitality projects have brand-mandated specifications, a fixed soft-opening date tied to marketing and franchise agreements, and complex life safety requirements. A GC without hotel experience will miss brand PIP requirements and struggle to coordinate the FF&E installation sequence with construction closeout."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What is a hotel PIP and why does it matter in construction?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "A PIP (property improvement plan) is the brand's specification document defining required finishes, furniture standards, and systems for a property to earn or maintain flag certification. PIPs must be incorporated into the construction documents before permit submission — retrofitting PIP requirements after construction begins is expensive and delays opening."
        }
      },
      {
        "@type": "Question",
        "name": "What permits are required to build a hotel?",
        "acceptedAnswer": {
          "@type": "Answer",
          "text": "At minimum: a building permit covering structural, architectural, and life safety; separate MEP permits (mechanical, electrical, plumbing); a fire suppression permit; and a health department permit for any food service or pool. High-rise, historic district, or coastal properties trigger additional state or federal review layers."
        }
      }
    ]
  }
]
